{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/how-to-create-a-c-project-using-ceres-solver-f3d67c8044f3", "time": 1683008791.7037, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/how-to-create-a-c-project-using-ceres-solver-f3d67c8044f3/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "How to create a C++ project using Ceres Solver? | by Jihong Ju \ud83e\udd13 | Towards Data Science", "h1": "How to create a C++ project using Ceres Solver?", "description": "I guess most of you already know a bit what Ceres Solver is about. For those of you who haven\u2019t heard about it, Ceres Solver is one of the most popular open-source libraries out there for solving\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "http://ceres-solver.org/", "anchor_text": "Ceres Solver", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-linear_least_squares", "anchor_text": "Non-linear Least Squares", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "http://ceres-solver.org/users.html", "anchor_text": "its official website", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "http://ceres-solver.org/installation.html", "anchor_text": "installation page", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "http://ceres-solver.org/installation.html#getting-the-source-code", "anchor_text": "Ceres\u2019 website.", "paragraph_index": 4}, {"url": "http://ceres-solver.org/nnls_tutorial.html#hello-world", "anchor_text": "HelloWorld", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "http://ceres-solver.org/nnls_tutorial.html#hello-world", "anchor_text": "HelloWorld", "paragraph_index": 8}, {"url": "https://ceres-solver.googlesource.com/ceres-solver/+/master/examples", "anchor_text": "Ceres\u2019 git repository", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://cmake.org/cmake/help/latest/guide/tutorial/index.html", "anchor_text": "the CMake build system", "paragraph_index": 11}, {"url": "https://medium.com/heuristics/c-application-development-part-2-cmakelists-txt-e415b5b387dc", "anchor_text": "C++ application development series", "paragraph_index": 13}, {"url": "https://medium.com/@aakashmallik?source=post_page-----e415b5b387dc----------------------", "anchor_text": "Aakash Mallik", "paragraph_index": 13}, {"url": "http://ceres-solver.org/installation.html#installing-exporting-a-project-that-uses-ceres", "anchor_text": "Installing / Exporting a project that uses Ceres", "paragraph_index": 14}, {"url": "http://ceres-solver.org/installation.html#", "anchor_text": "Ceres\u2019 installation guide", "paragraph_index": 15}], "all_paragraphs": ["I guess most of you already know a bit what Ceres Solver is about. For those of you who haven\u2019t heard about it, Ceres Solver is one of the most popular open-source libraries out there for solving large, complicated optimization problems. One of the highlighted features of Ceres Solver is being able to solve Non-linear Least Squares problems with bounds constraints. It is widely used in Robotics for problems like Bundle Adjustment and SLAM. A collection of users and applications can be found on its official website.", "Though Ceres Solver (referred to as Ceres in the rest of the article) has great documentation and hands-on tutorials to help new users get started. I found the information about how to create a new project using Ceres is somewhat hidden in the official guide. And that is exactly what this story is about.", "First of all, we need to install Ceres before we can use it. In this section, we will talk about how to build and install Ceres as a static library on a Ubuntu machine. If you are using a different operating system or you rather prefer to build Ceres as a shared library, please follow the instructions on the installation page.", "We start with the dependencies recommended for Ubuntu:", "Then we get the source code from Ceres\u2019 website. At the time of writing, the latest stable version is 1.14.0. Please adjust the version accordingly in the following commands:", "Now we\u2019ve compiled Ceres successfully. We should be able to run the HelloWorld example of Ceres.", "The last step is to install Ceres into the previously specified install directory:", "Depending on the install directory, you may or may not need sudo permission.", "In the previous section, we have talked about building and installing Ceres-Solver as a static library. We\u2019ve also run the HelloWorld example shipped with Ceres. The next step is to be able to compile our own HelloWorld program and start exploring the magic world of Ceres.", "To achieve that, we will create a simple project that looks like this:", "helloworld.cc is just the source code for the HellowWorld example we run before. You can get it from Ceres\u2019 git repository. There are many other examples available too, including but not limited to a circle fitting example, a bundle adjustment example, 2D & 3D examples of pose graph optimization, etc.", "CMakeLists.txt contains the information about how to build our helloworld.cc using the CMake build system:", "Note that Ceres officially supports CMake 2.8 for backward compatibility. But it will not hurt us to adopt the CMake 3.x style in 2020.", "If you are not familiar with the CMake build system, I highly recommend the C++ application development series by Aakash Mallik.", "If you want to distribute your project which uses Ceres, please refer to Installing / Exporting a project that uses Ceres for more information.", "Hopefully, this shortened version of Ceres\u2019 installation guide is helpful for those of you who are not familiar with CMake.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Ff3d67c8044f3&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fhow-to-create-a-c-project-using-ceres-solver-f3d67c8044f3&source=post_page---two